═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
PART B — THE THERMODYNAMICS IS CORRECT
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

The Flory-Huggins free energy of mixing (per lattice site):

    ΔF_mix / kT  =  (phi/N) ln(phi)  +  (1-phi) ln(1-phi)  +  chi · phi · (1-phi)

Second derivative w.r.t. phi:

    d²(ΔF)/d(phi)²  =  1/(N·phi)  +  1/(1-phi)  -  2·chi

Spinodal condition (instability boundary):

    chi_spinodal  =  (1/2) · [ 1/(N·phi)  +  1/(1-phi) ]

Code matches all three formulas exactly. Flory (1942) Polymer Solutions,
Chapter 12. Brangwynne et al. 2009. Hyman et al. 2014. The physics is
faithfully implemented. Math is not in question.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
PART C — THE TEXT→POLYMER MAPPING IS HAND-WAVED
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

The shipped code uses:

    N    = len(text.split())                                    # word count
    phi  = (count of chars in "\n*-:1234567890!") / len(text)   # "formatting fraction"

Two structural problems:

C.1 — N as "polymer chain length" is physically arbitrary.
      Flory-Huggins N is the degree of polymerization of a single chain
      species. Mapping "word count of a passage" to "chain length" has
      no defensible physical correspondence. Worse: it makes chi_s a
      DECREASING function of text length, which means LONGER NATURAL
      PROSE GETS FLAGGED AS RLHF FOR PURELY LENGTH REASONS. Empirically
      verified in PART D.

C.2 — Treating digits 0-9 as "low-complexity formatting characters" is
      backwards. In Alice's actual conversation, numerical content
      ("STT confidence 0.31", "soma stress 0.41", timestamps) is
      high-information BIOLOGICAL signal. The detector flags it as
      RLHF because "0123456789" are in the formatting alphabet.
      Empirically verified in PART D.

C.3 — The most common real RLHF leak shape — preamble phrases like
      "Sure!", "Great question!", "Let me break this down" — has LOW
      character-level formatting density and short length, so it
      slips under the spinodal threshold. Verified in PART D.

