PART F — TWO PATHS FORWARD
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

F.1 — KEEP Flory-Huggins, FIX the mapping. The physics is beautiful.
      The mapping is the bug. A defensible mapping might be:

        - phi   = fraction of low-perplexity tokens (need an LM to score)
        - N     = a fixed reference chain length (e.g., N=20 for "one
                  paragraph"), not text-length-dependent
        - chi   = calibrated against a labelled corpus, not picked

      With these changes, the spinodal boundary becomes a physics-based
      thresholding of an LM-perplexity feature, which is principled.
      Flory-Huggins then earns its keep.

F.2 — DEMOTE Flory-Huggins to one feature, WIRE multi-feature detector.
      The 3 leaks AG31 logged are shape-pattern leaks. Detect them with
      a small ensemble:

        - line-initial bullet density
        - numbered-enumeration regex hits (e.g., r"^\d+\. ", r"^\* ")
        - "Sure!"/"Great question!" preamble regex
        - colon-terminated heading lines
        - + Flory-Huggins as ONE more feature (its current form)

      Then logistic-regress these against the labelled corpus and gag
      when score > threshold.

Either path solves the RLHF leak problem. Pure Flory-Huggins as currently
mapped does not.

